response:
Let's use the given forms in the question statement. Here, we need to find $\boxed{\textbf{0}}$.</think>
<answer>Let's start by finding $f(g(x))$ and $g(f(x))$ separately and then evaluate their difference. We'll use the same functions defined as $$f(x) = 6x - 9$$ $$g(x) = \frac{x}{3} + 2$$

So now we have to solve for $f (g(x)) - g(f(x))$.
\begin{align*}
f (g(x)) &= f (\frac{x}{3} +2)\\
    &= 6 \left(\frac{x}{3} +2 \right) - 9\\
    &= 2x + 12 - 9\\
    &= 2x + 3
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
g (f(x)) &= g (6x - 9)\\
    &= \frac{1}{3} (6x-9) + 2\\
    &= 2x-3+2\\
    &= 2x-1
\end{align*}
So we have to find $$f (g(x)) - g (f(x))$$
\begin{align*}
f (g(x)) - g (f(x)) &= (2x+3) -(2x-1)\\
&= \boxed{4}
\end{align*}
</answer>

